  "prompt": "If we evolved from apes then why are there still apes around today?",
  "response": "This is a common misunderstanding about evolution. Humans and modern apes did not evolve directly from each other, but we share a common ancestor. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. Humans and modern apes evolved from a shared ancestor species that lived millions of years ago, not that one directly descended from the other.\n\n2. Evolution is like a branching tree, where different species can evolve from the same ancestral population and coexist.\n\n3. Different environmental pressures and adaptations led humans and other ape species to develop along separate evolutionary paths.\n\n4. Just as humans didn't replace their ancestral species, other ape species also continued to exist and adapt to their environments.\n\n5. Modern humans (Homo sapiens) and modern apes are \"cousin\" species that diverged from a common ancestor, each evolving differently to suit their specific ecological niches.\n\nScientists have substantial fossil and genetic evidence supporting this understanding of human and ape evolution. The theory explains why multiple species can exist simultaneously, even if they share common ancestral origins.",
